      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here is the `check_permission` function that handles role hierarchy and attribute requirements:\n\n```python\ndef check_permission(user, resource, action):\n    # Define role hierarchy from highest to lowest priority\n    hierarchy = {\n        'admin': 4,\n        'manager': 3,\n        'editor': 2,\n        'viewer': 1\n    }\n    \n    # Verify the user's role meets the minimum requirement for the resource\n    if hierarchy.get(user.role, 0) < hierarchy.get(resource.required_role, 0):\n        return False\n\n    # If a specific attribute is required, the user must possess it\n    if resource.required_attribute and resource.required_attribute not in user.attributes:\n        return False\n\n    return True\n```\n\nThis implementation assigns a numeric priority to roles so the hierarchy logic works correctly, but it also checks if the user has the specific attribute before granting access if one is defined. You can run your test suite immediately to verify it passes.",
